--- PART 4: CONNECTION TO PRODUCT LAW ---

The product law sign(h_hat[{a,b}]) = chi(ab) requires that
the dominant D^{2n} contributions all have sign = chi(ab).

From the resonance cascade:
  sign(D^{2n} deg-2) * chi(ab) = chi(q) at onset

So: sign = chi(q) * chi(ab).
For product law: need chi(q) * chi(ab) = chi(ab), i.e., chi(q) = +1.
But at p=19: chi(3) = -1, so 3-resonant pairs violate this!

The RESOLUTION must come from higher-order terms overwhelming D^4.
The co-participation theorem says: 3-resonant pairs have NO
additive coupling through 3-cycles, which means their H-contribution
comes from HIGHER-order cycle interactions, not from 3-cycle overlap.

At p=19:
  q=3 pairs: copart=N, sign(D^4)=-chi(ab), but D^6,D^8,... have +chi(ab)
  q=5 pairs: copart=N, sign(D^6)=+chi(ab)
  q=7 pairs: copart=Y, sign(D^8)=+chi(ab)
  q=9 pairs: copart=Y, sign(D^10)=+chi(ab)

The key question: for q=3 pairs at p=19, do D^6+D^8+... outweigh D^4?
This is the content of the p=19 product law computation.
